","–1448":"–1448","1360–1402":"1360–1402","1386–1444":"1386–1444","1402–1448":"1402–1448","1318–1359":"1318–1359","1318–1386":"1318–1386","before 1402":"before 1402","before 1376":"before 1376","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","17 June 1418":"17 June 1418","1448":"1448","1338":"1338","after 1402":"after 1402","1337":"1337","1359":"1359","1402":"1402","after 17 June 1418":"after 17 June 1418","1444":"1444","about 1339":"about 1339","about 1359":"about 1359","1386":"1386","about 1386":"about 1386","1418":"1418","1318":"1318","1339":"1339","Ramsbury, Wiltshire, England":"Ramsbury, Wiltshire, England","Lymington, Hampshire, England":"Lymington, Hampshire, England","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","Popham, Hampshire, England":"Popham, Hampshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Popham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in Hampshire, so called from an unattested short form of Old English <i>popel</i> ‘pebble’ + Old English <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’.","History: The Popham Colony was the first organized attempt to establish an English colony on the shores of what is now known as New England, then called Northern Virginia. George Popham of Hunstworth, Somerset, England, helped establish the colony at the mouth of the Kennebec River in 1607. It lasted for little over a year until it was abandoned in 1608. Although George died that same year, he may have had descendants or relatives with him as there are Pophams in the US who trace their family roots to the colony."],"variants":[{"name":"Poplin","meanings":["English: at least in part, a variant of   Popham  ."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":43,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry Popham was born about 1339, in Popham, Hampshire, England, his father, John de Popham, was 22 and his mother, Sybil de Saint-Martin, was 22. He married Joan Frank before 1376. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 17 June 1418, in Lymington, Hampshire, England, at the age of 80, and was buried in Lymington, Hampshire, England."},"et":{"about 1339–17 June 1418":"umbes 1339–17. juuni 1418","1338–1360":"1338–1360","1339–1418":"1339–1418","–1448":"–1448","1360–1402":"1360–1402","1386–1444":"1386–1444","1402–1448":"1402–1448","1318–1359":"1318–1359","1318–1386":"1318–1386","before 1402":"enne 1402","before 1376":"enne 1376","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","17 June 1418":"17. juuni 1418","1448":"1448","1338":"1338","after 1402":"pärast 1402","1337":"1337","1359":"1359","1402":"1402","after 17 June 1418":"pärast 17. juunit 1418","1444":"1444","about 1339":"umbes 1339","about 1359":"umbes 1359","1386":"1386","about 1386":"umbes 1386","1418":"1418","1318":"1318","1339":"1339","Ramsbury, Wiltshire, England":"Ramsbury, Wiltshire, England","Lymington, Hampshire, England":"Lymington, Hampshire, England","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","Popham, Hampshire, England